headline: Jesse and Emily hunt for the perfect Christmas tree
subHeadline: Jesse Watters and Emily Compagno find a Christmas tree for 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino, co-host
utterances.utterance: Hello, everyone. I'm Dana Perino, along with Emily Campagno, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5 o'clock in New York City. This is "The Five." Merry Christmas Eve, everyone. We're excited to have you join us for our celebration. We have tons of fun for you tonight, including reaction to our first ever Christmas grab bag of stories making headlines, a special Christmas edition of Supermarket Showdown. And, we are squaring off to see who will be crowned The Quiz Show champion. Plus, we've been waiting all year for our Secret Santa gift exchange. It's our biggest one yet. Don't miss the annual tradition. But first, there's no better way to get into the Christmas spirit than by cutting down your own Christmas tree. So Jesse and Emily went out on a little adventure to a local tree farm to show us how it's done. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters, co-host
utterances.utterance: We're here at the Hidden Pond Christmas Tree Farm in Mendham, New Jersey, with Christian Nicholson, the owner.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno, guest co-host
utterances.utterance: I have to say, Christian, I'm so excited. I have never cut down a Christmas tree before. This is like a life-long dream of mine.

utterances.speaker: Christian Nicholson
utterances.utterance: Well, what you're going to realize when you get done is it's not so much about the tree, it's about the memories and about the spirit of Christmas when you come out to a real Christmas tree farm. So we're going to take a drive out to the fields, and take a look at some of the trees. Jesse, we'd like you to drive the tractor. Do you know how to drive a stick shift? Emily, how about you? Do you know how to drive a stick shift?

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Yes, I do. All Mack Truck [spelled phonetically].

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Try to keep it under the speed limit.

utterances.speaker: Christian Nicholson
utterances.utterance: That's a really nice tree right there.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: What do you think the perfect tree would look like for The Five?

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Obviously, as big as possible that can fit in that space.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: So this is maybe around 5-4. This is like Gutfeld size.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: He needs a few more years.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: This one is leaning a little to the left.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Some of these, actually, they're getting good if we keep walking. These are some big ones back here.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: I feel like we're in an orphanage and all the kids are like, "Pick me, pick me." Like all the trees are like, "Pick me, pick me."

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: This is nice. Oh, this is a taker.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Ooh, how about this one? Wait, it's a little crooked.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: I like it. I think it's got good size. It's got nice shape.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Perfect tip. Should I saw it down?

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Oh, I'm kind of impressed, actually.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: All right, let's go bag it and tag it. Emily Compagno: All right, I'm ready.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Okay. Don't shove it in my face. Oh, great. That's so easy.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: All right, Emily. We came, we sawed, and we conquered.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Merry Christmas. Let's throw it back to the car and ride it to "The Five." Here we go. All right. In the elevator.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Ah, you have the lights on.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Although got to decorate it. Producers? Let's go.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Well done, guys. Not the first time you ever did that?

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: No, I've done it many times. That's why I sawed it so fast.

utterances.speaker: Greg Gutfeld, co-host
utterances.utterance: Wait, how come she was driving the ATV and not you?

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: As we saw, I don't drive stick.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Never learned. Never learned. Emily Compagno: It was a tractor, which I drove and hauling the flatbed with people on it, a bunch of people and the tree, it was awesome. That tree farm was incredible. It was my first time.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: How did you -- how did you feel killing a living thing?

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: I felt bad. That's why I thanked the tree stump after.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: We all -- no, we planted some seeds to, you know, replenish.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams, co-host
utterances.utterance: All right, let me just say --

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: But the thing is, you get the tree back, and there's still bugs in the tree.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: One time my parents sawed it off in Pennsylvania, brought it all the way to Long Island, and then that night they heard my cat screaming, and they found out a squirrel had embedded itself in the tree. It escaped in the middle of the night. Emily Compagno: Oh, my --

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: The other thing that I love about this is, when you put it in that plastic wrapping thing because, you know, initially, they -- like when they -- sometimes they do a fresh cut so that when you get it home, the tree can still absorb water.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: But what they do right at the end is they stick it in this plastic thing, and it reminds me of a wood chipper.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: What if they put me in there? Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: A lot of people might want to, Juan.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: That might be a good -- that might be a handy thing to have.

utterances.speaker: Greg Gutfeld
utterances.utterance: Yeah, the wrapping, the wrapping tube. They should apply that to other things. Like imagine just putting anything in that tube, and it comes out all wrapped up like your gym stuff. Like you're going to the gym, you just throw all your crap, and it goes "whoop splokkk" into this like little kind of mesh thing.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: Well, then what it reminds me of the most is at the airports now, they have luggage things that are like that.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: I think if you're going overseas --

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Well, that was really super cute. Thanks for going out there to do that. We have another one --

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Yeah, it was super cute. So it just wouldn't feel like Christmas in New York City without indulging in some delicious deserts. There -- two people here at this table went with me to Serendipity. They have really big sweet tooths, all right? Unforgettable tasty treats. Watch.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Hi, everyone. We are at one of the best place that's New York City has to offer. There's especially no place better to be than on the holidays. We're at Serendipity, which is a famous place. And we have Chef Joe who --

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: -- is going to show us and tell us a bit about these iconic desserts.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Well, I'll give it a shot.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: I've never had a proper banana split in my life.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: So you would go to the store and get it?

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Do you have a favorite dessert for Christmas, Juan?

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: Well, my wife makes a banana cream pie that's to die for.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: My grandmother on my mother's side would make an apple pie, like this dessert, and there would be a cherry pie usually. But I'll definitely do something chocolate.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: You know what? That cinnamon ice cream is out of this world.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: It is. What if you -- what if you put cinnamon in your chocolate, Juan?

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: [LAUGHS] Geez, that sounds a little looped [spelled phonetically].

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Who comes up with these things?

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Ugh! Well -- sorry, making a mess at Serendipity.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: This is the kind of chocolate cake I like. It's nice, moist. It looks so beautiful.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Did you guys have a bite of this cake?

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: If you guys could have any dessert every day for the rest of your life, what would you have? Juan Williams: If I was on death row, I think I'd take this Broadway.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: You want the ice cream and the cheesecake at the same time?

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: You know I'm going to be a fat man. You're going to make fun of me.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: No. You have the best -- you have the best metabolism of anybody.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: All right. Okay, you're going to love this the most out of all of them. Watch.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: You know what I noticed? Greg wasn't in any of those. Where were you?

utterances.speaker: Greg Gutfeld
utterances.utterance: I was busy. I'm not a big fan of watching people eat. Sorry. It's like kind of grosses me out. It's like you know in movies, whenever they have scenes -- or it's usually like they're -- people go to lunch, and they're all talking when they're eating, it's like, "You don't need that. Just don't have -- Jesse Watters: Well, they tell politicians, "Never eat on camera."

utterances.speaker: Greg Gutfeld
utterances.utterance: Yes, exactly. Although you all did a good job eating on camera. Nothing was dripping down.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: No, we did a good job.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Do you appreciate that constructive criticism?

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Appreciated that. I mean, it is an amazing place, Serendipity. And they actually have their own line of ice cream, and they gave us some here. I got the Outrageous Banana Split. You can get these in lots of stores.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: So, Juan, I have the one you liked, the Forbidden Broadway Sundae.

utterances.utterance: Man, let me tell you something, it's awesome.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: Awesome. But this isn't bad, Salty Carmel Pretzel --

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Oh, I like that. I'll switch --

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: You know what they say about the American diet? Salt and sugar.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: But every time -- everything they -- everything they said that day, Juan would say, "Oh, that's my favorite." "Oh, no, that's my favorite."

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: -- is pretty cool for Christmas, let me tell you, because it's -- -- like a child's wonderland, but except I don't see, we didn't see many kids in there because the adults are all -- and they have --

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: -- you can buy in a powder and I sent some up to the ranch for this Christmas --

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: Have a good time. We are all set? Everybody good?

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: Yeah, me and some ice cream.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: We have more to come? All right, eat up. Coming up, our amazing Secret Santa reveal that you do not want to miss. I am very excited about this one. But first, we're weighing in on some festive topics in Christmas grab bag with Emily when The Five returns.

utterances.speaker: Emily Compagno
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. It's time now for our Christmas grab bag of holiday topics. First up, mall Santas beware: Video chat companies are now offering families the chance for their kids to virtually chat with Old Saint Nick from the comfort of home. Juan, do you think, what do you think about this? Do you think it should replace the experience? I took Duchess [spelled phonetically] to take a photo with a sleigh this week at a mall and it was wonderful.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: I agree. So, I don't know, people who watch this show know I just recently showed pictures of my grandkids at the mall with the Santa. And in fact, it was funny because the Santa remembered them from the year before.

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: But I think the objection here --

utterances.speaker: Juan Williams
utterances.utterance: -- and this goes way back in my family life -- is you have to stand in line if you go to the mall Santa, and sometimes the line can be, like, inexorable. Like just the line goes on, and on, and on, and on. But it's all part of the family tradition. It's like, "Yeah, we go through this." It's like going to the Thanksgiving Day parade here in New York where there's these big crowds and it's sometimes cold and windy, and even icy or snowy. But you're standing there, and then the floats come, and memories are made. So, I think the comfort of home, maybe for a disabled child, I get it. But beyond that, this is laziness.

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters
utterances.utterance: A friend of mine in his 30s just decided to make a little extra cash for the holiday season and became a mall Santa and just sat there, had kids sit in his lap, and collected a lot of cash for the holiday season. So, if you're looking for a little side hustle around this time of year, it's a great opportunity.

utterances.speaker: Dana Perino
utterances.utterance: I like it that Santa is not afraid of technology and just rolls with the times, like not afraid to get on the video chat --

utterances.speaker: Greg Gutfeld
utterances.utterance: Well, you know I don't like children. So, if I were -- this would be the way I would do it if I were Santa. I was a shopping mall Santa --

utterances.utterance: -- in Cherry Hill at the, at the mall in Cherry Hill.

utterances.speaker: Greg Gutfeld

utterances.speaker: Jesse Watters

utterances.utterance: All right. Up next, we all look forward to doing Secret Santa here on The Five. But apparently, not everyone is a fan of the Christmas tradition. Some millennials say that they want to ban the gift exchange because it triggers anxiety for them at work. Greg, to you first.

utterances.utterance: The little bah humbug. All right, up next: A surprising trend under the tree this year. Many people are using Christmas gifts to send passive-aggressive messages.
